  "prompt": "What is a store credit?",
  "response": "Store credit is a form of payment or compensation issued by a retailer that can be used for future purchases within that specific store. It is typically given in the following situations:\n\n1. Product returns: When a customer returns an item without a receipt or outside the standard return window.\n\n2. Exchange for defective merchandise: If a product is faulty or doesn't meet the customer's expectations.\n\n3. Compensation for poor service or experience: As a goodwill gesture to maintain customer satisfaction.\n\n4. Promotional offers: Some stores provide credit as part of marketing campaigns or loyalty programs.\n\nStore credit usually comes in the form of a gift card, paper voucher, or digital credit that can be applied to future purchases at the same retailer. Unlike cash refunds, store credit can only be used within that specific store and often has an expiration date.\n\nThe main characteristics of store credit include:\n- Limited to use at a specific retailer\n- Cannot typically be converted to cash\n- Often has an expiration date\n- Used as a form of store-specific payment",
